defaultNothing necessary.
defaultGreendefaultEncourage committees to make use of the support of the Scrutiny Unit and to discuss with the National Audit Office how its programme of work might help support the work of the committee.
defaultRecent programme of NAO 
defaultsecondees
default from NAO for programme of work on statistics and for procurement inquiry.  Regular liaison at staff level with NAO about PASC future programme.
defaultSupport routinely sought from Scrutiny Unit, 
defaulteg
default for annual 
defaultfinancial scrutiny of the Cabinet Office and for scrutiny of main estimates. Legal advice on general matters (charity law, for example) sought from the Scrutiny Unit legal specialists when necessary.
defaultContinue as currently.
defaultGreendefaultAs a model of ‘best practice’, we recommend that committees:
defaulta) have a candid discussion amongst themselves about how they see their purpose, and what they wish to achieve 
defaultover the length of the Parliament;
defaultCommittee will be holding an away day on 3 December.
defaultCould be discussed by Committee at its away day.
defaultGreendefaultb) identify what are the most important functions of their department’s responsibilities and design a programme of scrutiny to assess whether the department’s objectives have been fulfilled;
defaultNot done formally.
defaultCould be discussed by Committee at its away day.
defaultGreendefaultc) clearly record their conclusions and remind themselves of them when considering proposals for inquiry and programme planning;
defaultConclusions clearly recorded in bold in reports; clerks and inquiry managers ensure previous conclusions are considered. In notes for 
defaultdiscussion on future inquiries, staff will make sure previous relevant committee conclusions are clearly identified.
defaultTo continue to look back at previous conclusions when drawing up future programme and 
defaultconducting inquiries.
defaultAmberdefaultd) review this at least annually, with an “away day” or at least a longer, less formal discussion than is possible at a regular deliberative meeting;
defaultCommittee has agreed to an away day.
defaultHold away day.
defaultGreendefaulte) canvass opinion among the key players in their subject area about their performance.
defaultAt their meeting on 16 October the Committee agreed to seek feedback from witnesses and journalists to inform their away 
defaultday on 3 December.
default&#xa0;
defaultAmberdefaultWe commend to other committees the practice of publishing strategic objectives, and of consulting their department and other stakeholders on them.
defaultObjectives published for each inquiry, but overall objectives for PASC’s work not published.
default&#xa0;
defaultCommittee to develop strategic objectives at away day.
defaultAmberdefaultWe recommend that, before they launch an inquiry, committees agree a comprehensive minute setting out what they hope to achieve, and the likelihood of success.
defaultObjectives agreed and published for each inquiry. 
defaultCommittee to discuss the merits of having a more comprehensive minute.
defaultAmberdefaultWe recommend that in future inquiries, as 
defaulta matter of routine, committees include consideration of the financial aspects and implications of the policies being examined.
defaultPASC already does this, and 
defaulthas identified more that it will do in future.
defaultContinue to do so, 
defaultseeking specialist financial input if necessary from Scrutiny Unit.
defaultGreendefaultWe encourage committees to hold evidence sessions at least annually with ministers and departmental accounting officers, and include within these sessions consideration of how departments evaluate and take decisions on spending, and how they assess the effectiveness of the spending they undertake.
defaultPASC already does this. Staff use the advice of the Scrutiny Unit when preparing for these sessions.
defaultContinue as currently.
defaultGreendefaultWe encourage committees to review departments’ Mid-Year Reports when published, using them to identify relevant issues and questions relating to finance and performance
defaultThis will be the first year that the Cabinet Office has published a Mid-Year Report.
defaultTo keep under review.
defaultGreendefaultWe recommend that committees experiment with different approaches, such as appointing a 
defaultrapporteur
default to lead on a particular inquiry, or choosing “lead questioners” for an evidence session.
defaultThis happens informally, based on the level of interest of individual members. Committee considered its questioning techniques at training session on effective questioning on 20 June 2013.
defaultCommittee to discuss if they wish to have formally-agreed 
defaultrapporteurs
default or lead questioners.
defaultAmberdefaultWe recommend that committees make every effort to broaden their range of witnesses, and to take into account the principles of diversity and inclusion in planning their inquiries and committee programme.
defaultCommittee staff are conscious of diversity issues when drawing up witness plans. Staff recently audited proportion of male / female PASC witnesses: only one in six witnesses were female (17%). 
defaultStaff will continue to monitor and search for viable alternative witnesses where possible.
defaultAmberdefaultCommittees should bear in mind the option of commissioning research when planning their long-term strategies, and, if necessary, the House authorities should increase the money available for this 
defaultpurpose.
defaultCommissioning research is considered. For example, PASC commissioned polling from 
defaultYouGov
default in connection with its work on public engagement in policy making 
defaultand on national strategy.
defaultContinue as currently.
